1. in the Dockerfile ENV key=value => to set env var in a Dockerfile
2. to get the env vars from an image => docker inspect <imagename>
3. to get env vars for a container => docker inspect <container id>
4. to set env var to a container use => docker run -e key=value



lsblk => to see disks and partitions
file -s /dev/<devname> => to display info about specific dev (disk,part)
mount <devname> <mount point> => to mount a part to a sepecfic dir
to persist you need to add that to /etc/fstab
fdisk => to create a partition from a disk
n to create new partition 
w to write the partition ( to save changes)
mkfs.<fsname> | mkfs -t <fsname>  ==> xfs, ext4, ext3
mount -a => to apply the /etc/fstab file now
by default fstab file is read during boot


